This paper is about language modeling, which is a subfield of natural language processing (NLP) and falls under the category of computer science (cs). The paper specifically addresses the limitations of Softmax-based models in NLP, which suggests that it belongs to the sub-category of computational linguistics (cs.CL). Additionally, the paper proposes a method to improve language modeling, which involves optimizing the parameters of a neural network, indicating that it could also belong to the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the paper uses language data from Penn Treebank and WikiText-2, which suggests that it could also belong to the sub-category of computer vision (cs.CV), which often involves processing and analyzing textual data.
